  <title>The Egress Boundary Is the Right Place to Freeze</title>
  <meta name="author" content="A2Web Harness">
</head>
<body>
<article>
  <h1>The Egress Boundary Is the Right Place to Freeze</h1>
  <p>When you record a web fetch for replay, the tempting shortcut is to
  freeze the final response object. That shortcut quietly removes the most
  important thing under test: the decision the system makes about how hard
  to try. Freeze the answer and you can never again ask whether the gate
  would have escalated, whether the ladder would have descended, or whether
  a different tier would have produced a better result.</p>
  <p>Freezing at the egress boundary keeps every one of those decisions
  live. The orchestrator still runs. The gate still evaluates the page
  against the question. The escalation logic still fires. Only the bytes
  coming back from the network are canned, and those bytes are exactly what
  the live world handed us at capture time.</p>
  <p>This is why the cassette stores one frozen exchange per outbound URL,
  keyed by the request the pipeline actually made. A raw fetch maps to one
  exchange; an archive lookup maps to several. Replay serves each by URL and
  refuses, loudly, to invent one it does not have.</p>
  <p>The same principle extends upward. The rendered browser DOM is a frozen
  input, not a frozen verdict. The language model is a recorded egress, not
  a hand-written stub. Every layer is the real layer, fed frozen inputs, so
  the answer a replay produces is the answer the real pipeline would have
  produced from those inputs.</p>
  <p>The payoff is a regression test that fails for the right reason: a code
  change moved the answer, not the site drifting underneath you. That single
  property is what turns a pile of saved pages into an instrument.</p>
</article>
</body>
</html>
